I think they tried to figure out a way to optimize their ordering system to expedite customers and get the line moving as quickly as possible, but really fell short and should rethink it. A man with a tablet asked what want. I tell him "the special chicken tomato mozarella paired with a garden vegetable soup". Quite a mouthful if you ask me. I get to the sandwich maker and he asks what I'm having. I stumble my words because I thought I just ordered already. He walked away midway through my explanation and I had to repeat myself. He gives me my sandwich and  not my soup saying 'you get your soup at the cash'. I get to the cash, who asked what I ordered.... AGAIN?! I repeat myself, and the cashier doesn't get my soup. I stand at the end counter and another person comes and asks me FOR THE FOURTH TIME what soup I'm getting and what size. This is not streamlined customer service. I'm still giving three stars cause the food wasn't actually bad.

This busy location never seems to be at its best whenever I go. The line is generally quite long, but doesn't seem to move as efficiently as other locations at busy periods. There seems to be a 50/50 chance that my order is made correctly (usually wrong or missing toppings), and they almost always fail to stock their cookies, necessitating asking if there are more behind the counter. In the end, the food still tastes good, but given the gloomy location and seemingly always unclean tables, I never feel a desire to go there other than out of convenience.

One of the few places in the area where you can get a fully satisfying, affordable $5 meal (cup of addictive Chili + free cup of water) in a comfortable venue of free WiFi with clean tables and chairs. 1-star less as I couldn't find any outlet that makes it impossible to eat here 3x/day plus snacks.

I was staying at the Hyatt in downtown Chicago and didn't have much money with me. I thought I'd look for Subway but in asking for directions someone said "There's a potbelly pig sandwich shop down there." That's all I needed to hear. After eating in one in Washington DC last week and loving it, I headed straight there. I really like the skinny sandwiches, particularly the mushroom on multigrain toasted bread. The cost for my sandwich and a drink was about $6.75.
